From: wilcox@kpw104.rh.psu.edu (Ken Wilcox)
Subject: Re: Security
Date: 1 Dec 1993 02:40:10 GMT

Andy (pi92ae@lelle.pt.hk-r.se) wrote:


:    Upgrade your bios. All the versions of AMI bios ( I think) have password 
:    protection on it.

: Not all has AMI bios. I don't exactly know what bios, but the machine
: is a new AST Bravo 486... Only "bootup password" supported.

I know but you can change it. That is just a thought.

:    : Now assume that someone boots from his own disk.. what possible harm
:    : can he do to the net ?? If he trashes the local LINUX machine's HD, we
:    : have backups.. But what can he do with stuff ob the net and so on?

:    What could he possible boot from his own disk that could do more damage 
:    than booting Linux single user. Certainly MSDOG won't have anything that you
:    could harm it with that is less then the capacity of one disk.

: I meant if he mounts the harddisk, copies in a new passwd file, with
: himself as root, what can he do to our nfs mounted disks on the net.

Well you can make Linux boot single user (root) off of the harddisk 
especially if you are using LILO. That is unaviodable.  I someone goes
to console and has complete and utter control over the computer. 

: I am not familiar to NFS and so on, the only thing I know are that you
: can mount a harddisk over the net, what authorities are required??

Yes, you can set the squashroot thing so that root can not write or even
read from the disk. Read the Linux Network Administrators Manual. That 
helps, thought me a lot of things.

:    : Can he send EMAIL from illegal host?

:    Anyone can do this from any where at any time.

: If it is what I am thinking of.. you mostly can trace the computer
: that the mail originates from.. or are there better ways??

Yes you can, it would be much the same thing though if he attempted to do
it from that machine.

-Ken Wilcox

