From: mrb@dtro.e-technik.th-darmstadt.de (Martin Boehnke)
Subject: Re: [Q]Faster SCSI patch
Date: 1 Dec 93 10:30:28

I used the patch successfully against the 0.99pl13q ALPHA kernel,
where the directory structure for the device drivers was allready
changed. 

As the result, I would guess it nearly doubled the speed
of my 386DX25 accessing a *very fast* DEC SCSI-Drive (DSP 3133L),
with an Adaptec 1542A.

In the meantime, the newest kernel is 0.99pl14. I checked the
patches out some minutes ago and found that they do *NOT WORK*
without adjustments:

-- Some SCSI-Bugs have been fixed, allready:
                linux/drivers/scsi/sd.c  (Hunk #11)
                linux/drivers/scsi/aha1542.c
                linux/drivers/scsi/aha1542.h
        You can savely ignore any reported errors on these files,
        do not apply reverse patch!

-- Others only work, if made by hand (because of other changes):
                linux/drivers/block/ll_rw_blk.c (Hunks #1 and #2)
                linux/fs/block_dev.c  (Hunk #1)

You apply the patches with the ... patch command ... 
(you allready guessed it :-):
        cd /usr/src/linux
        patch -p < /where_the_patch_is/kernel.diff

(I allways apply the patches inside of an Emacs-shell window,
so I can scroll back, to see if something went wrong.)
Compile the kernel, compile the bdflush process and install it,
install the kernel (keep a backup copy of your old kernel and update,
just in case ...) and boot. That's all!

Good Luck
--
